minimumTimeGap renamed to temporalResolution;
operations metadata provide further information on the allowed values for temporalResolution (but must be a duration, of course): - "AnyValue" - "AllowedValues" facets to define allowed durations (quite flexible - a list of specific durations can be provided, also value ranges) - "NoValue" - to define that temporal aggregation is not supported by that service
new property "target" - used to identify which information the client is interested in; the operation model has been simplified so that only one type of information can be queried per request (availability of observation data for a specific foi, procedure, property or a combination thereof - now also for a combination of all three of them); the response model is much simpler due to this change
TBD: should we define which target values a SOS must support (implying that some values are optional) - or should a SOS be forced to support all of them?
the three XXSelection properties are now used to identify which featuresOfInterest, procedures and observedProperties shall be included in the availability study; omitting the property in the request means that all values are of interest (e.g. all features of interest); in a request with target featureOfInterest, for example, the service can safely ignore the procedureSelection and propertySelection if they were contained in the request

observationCount is exact only at the instant of the request, and will quickly change if the database takes real-time updates from sensors which sample at 1 minute intervals
would observationCount be too hard to support in a real streaming application? Should it thus be optional (realized via additional requirements class and extension elements)?
Dependencies of external application schema and models not shown.

properties of the various types required in the previous response model have been merged into one type; this type provides availability information for the target specified in the request
featureOfInterest, procedure and (observed)property identify the respective observation properties (as it was done in XXInfo types from previous response model); which one is populated depends on requested target; for example, if featureOfInterest is the target then only featureOfInterest will be populated in DataAvailability elements of response - likewise, if procedureProperty is the target then both the procedure and property elements will be populated
observationCount - TBD; could make it optional in response and let service decide if it is supported
